Vet Notes: Subjective: Kuzco presented today for examination and wellness services (listed below). Kuzco has not received any vaccines yet. No C/S/V/D. No health concerns or recent
medications. Objective:
BCS: 5(1-9)
Gen: BAR, adequately hydrated, mm: pink, moist, CRT: 1.5 sec
Oral: no dental tartar/plaque, no gingivitis
EENT: no oculonasal discharge
CV: normal heart rate and rhythm, no murmurs or arrhythmias appreciated. Strong
synchronous pulses
Resp: Eupneic, no crackles or wheezes appreciated
Abdo: no palpable masses or fluid wave
Msk: adequate and symmetric muscling, no lameness
Neuro: appropriate mentation and ambulation
LN: no peripheral lymphadenopathy
Urogenital: 1descended testicle (1 undescended testicle).no preputial swelling or
discharge appreciated
Integ: full and clean hair coat, no ectoparasites appreciated
Assessment:
Apparently healthy for vaccines
-Cryptorchid
Plan:
Vaccines:
DAPPL: Right forelimb SQ
Bordetella: intranasal
Dewormer: Pyrantel (50mg/ml):0.5m L PO
Diagnostics:
-Intestinal Parasite Screening: Owner to collect sample and return for screening. Rx: Heartgard Plus (up to 25#) #1: administer 1 chew by mouth every 30 days. Continue for the lifetime of your pet. Additional Notes:
According to the American Animal Hospital Association vaccination guidelines, all
puppies should be vaccinated through 16 weeks of age in order to be considered fully
vaccinated (specifically for DAPP). Today, Kuzco received his first Distemper Adenovirus Parvovirus Parainfluenza (DAPP)
with Lepto as well as his bordetella vaccine. In 3-4 weeks from that visit (at 16 weeks
of age), Kuzco will receive the final DAPPL booster and his Rabies vaccine. Then, these
vaccines will be due in 1 year. Puppies are not considered fully vaccinated until 2 weeks
after her last booster. Until then it is important to keep him away from other dogs with
unknown vaccine status (dog parks, petsmart, groomers, etc.). Monitor for signs of vaccine reactions - if any significant swelling, hives, difficulty
breathing, vomiting, or diarrhea within the next 24 hours then P needs to be taken to an
emergency clinic for evaluation. Kuzco has 1 undescended testicle. Both testicles should be descended by 16 weeks of
age. Dogs with retained testicles are at a higher risk of developing testicular cancer
(sertoli cell tumor) or testicular torsion. It is highly recommended having Kuzco being
castrated at 6 months. Heartworm disease is transmitted through mosquitos. All it takes is one bite from one
infected mosquito to transmit the disease, which is potentially fatal. Heartworm disease
is present in all 50 states. Therefore, it is highly recommended that all pets are on
heartworm prevention for the duration of their lifetime. Heartworm and flea/tick
prevention can be started as early as 8 weeks of age. Heartworm disease testing
should be performed when the dog is 6 months of age, as the test detects adult
heartworms, and it takes 6 months for the worms to mature. Heartworm disease
testing should then be performed once every year after that. Page 2 of 3
